08/Nov/16 7:00 AM;jyellick;The queue size is intended to be configurable, and ultimately, we will coalesce the broadcast server paths to share this sort of configuration.

I do not however agree that we should turn this into a blocking all.  Making this a blocking call simply pushes the buffering into gRPC, so the gRPC must maintain a queue, and then block or fail.  By specifying the queue size in the application, the client can appropriately implement flow control.

If the client knows the queue size is set to 10 for instance, it can make sure that it sends only 10 requests, then sends only one request per ack it receives.  In this way, the client throttles itself to keep from overloading the server, dependent on the server's load.;;;
